aesthetics based on whether central and human size

The shooting angle of the first image is perfect, for it captures the corner of the wall, adding a sense of depth to the image.
The shooting angle of image 2 is too low.
The only drawback of the third image is the lack of depth, but the subject is positioned in the center of the frame, which is good.
In the fourth image, the subject is positioned too far to the left, making it aesthetically unpleasing.

The shooting angles in both image 1 and image 4 are excessively biased toward one side, resulting in a lack of aesthetic appeal and diminishing the emphasis on the core subject.
Image 2, however, achieves success in a manner reminiscent of Image 1 from the previous set— both capture a corner of the wall, with the subject positioned precisely beside it, enhancing the photograph's sense of depth and technological elegance.
For future shoots, placing the subject partially at the wall's corner may yield even better results.
As for Image 3, the subject is positioned roughly in the center, contributing to a commendable photographic outcome.
